  "summaries": [
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":1,"summary":"After Joshua's death, Judah and Simeon lead attacks against the Canaanites, but several tribes fail to fully drive out the inhabitants of their allotted lands."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":2,"summary":"An angel rebukes Israel for making covenants with the Canaanites; a new generation arises that forsakes the Lord, and the cyclical pattern of apostasy, oppression, and deliverance is established."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":3,"summary":"Israel intermarries with Canaanites and worships their gods; God raises up Othniel, Ehud, and Shamgar as judges to deliver the people from foreign oppressors."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":4,"summary":"The prophetess Deborah commissions Barak to fight Sisera's army; God grants Israel victory, and Jael kills Sisera by driving a tent peg through his head."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":5,"summary":"Deborah and Barak sing a triumphant victory hymn recounting God's power, the courage of the tribes, and the defeat of Sisera and the Canaanites."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":6,"summary":"Israel is oppressed by Midian; the angel of the Lord appears to Gideon and calls him to deliver Israel, and Gideon confirms the call through the fleece signs."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":7,"summary":"God reduces Gideon's army from 32,000 to 300 men, who defeat the Midianite host with trumpets, torches, and pitchers in a divinely orchestrated rout."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":8,"summary":"Gideon pursues and captures the kings of Midian, refuses an offer of kingship, but makes a golden ephod that becomes a snare to Israel."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":9,"summary":"Abimelech murders his seventy brothers and seizes power in Shechem; Jotham delivers the parable of the trees, and Abimelech is ultimately killed in battle."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":10,"summary":"After the judges Tola and Jair, Israel again turns to idolatry and is oppressed by the Philistines and Ammonites; they cry to God who rebukes then relents."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":11,"summary":"The outcast Jephthah is called to lead Gilead against Ammon, delivers Israel, but tragically fulfills a rash vow concerning his daughter."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":12,"summary":"The Ephraimites quarrel with Jephthah, leading to civil war and the death of 42,000 at the Jordan fords; three minor judges follow."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":13,"summary":"The angel of the Lord appears to Manoah's wife, announcing the birth of Samson as a Nazirite who will begin to deliver Israel from the Philistines."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":14,"summary":"Samson seeks a Philistine wife, kills a lion, and poses a riddle at his wedding feast that leads to conflict when his wife reveals the answer."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":15,"summary":"Samson takes revenge on the Philistines with burning foxes, slays a thousand men with a jawbone, and God miraculously provides water from the ground."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":16,"summary":"Samson is betrayed by Delilah, captured and blinded by the Philistines, and in a final act of strength pulls down the temple of Dagon upon himself and his enemies."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":17,"summary":"An Ephraimite named Micah establishes an idolatrous household shrine with a graven image and hires a wandering Levite as his personal priest."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":18,"summary":"Danite spies discover Micah's shrine, and the tribe of Dan steals his idols and Levite priest, establishing an unauthorized worship center at the conquered city of Laish."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":19,"summary":"A Levite's concubine is horrifically abused and killed by men of Gibeah in Benjamin; the Levite dismembers her body and sends it throughout Israel as a call to action."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":20,"summary":"All Israel unites against Benjamin for the crime at Gibeah; after two initial defeats, Israel prevails and nearly annihilates the entire tribe of Benjamin."},
    {"book":"Judges","chapter":21,"summary":"Israel mourns the near-extinction of Benjamin and devises ways to provide wives for the surviving 600 men, closing with the refrain that every man did what was right in his own eyes."}
  ],
